Latin America in the Fight Against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unparalleled size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
We must not meet the crisis hesitantly, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
Until now, the political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
Others, however, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These government leaders made the decision in the midst of the tragedy for a populist and divisive politics.
Latin America's top priority should be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving the healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
Moreover, Latin American states must reject export controls for medical supplies and other vital resources and must advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to U.S. President Donald Trump's reckless decision to freeze about $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global collaboration among health authorities to boost testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: not only has the Latin American domestic production been interrupted, but countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the missing tourism, fewer foreign remittances, and strong capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the collapse in demand.
To prevent this, bold measures are necessary to protect household incomes.
This means transfer payments to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for companies are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and social security costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. This is therefore crucial for a quick economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is at risk.
Many companies, especially the small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Postponing tax payments, payment deferrals, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented government guarantees on loans to ensure that banks can continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state-owned banks can play a leading role in this.
All in all, measures will probably differ from country to country, but overall, extraordinary budget resources will be needed everywhere except to speed up recovery.
The governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without exacerbating health risks.
The problem is that the budget leeway in Latin America is even tighter today than it was after the 2008 global financial crisis.
Thus, budget burdens must be cushioned by adjustments in areas of lower priority.
Here, the risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness exists, but this can be reduced by the governments' promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, especially for the small and less developed Latin American countries, an external support for the budget and balance of payments is urgently needed.
As both private companies and states take on higher deficits, the current account balances of the countries are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the history of modern financial markets – exacerbate the problem even further.
The resulting devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
It must take care of the short-term currency and budget needs of countries and continue to support the economies in this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
To do this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a new edition of the global reserve currency of the IMF – the Special Drawing Rights (SDRs) that should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although the SDRs are allocated to member countries in proportion to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation can be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the supervision of the Fund.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity to meet the strong credit demand that is expected by doubling the volume of new credit agreements immediately.
And finally, the Fund must, as traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in time, improve access to low-threshold tools with fast payout – such as its rapid financing instrument – or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can pass on the liquidity of the central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all the instruments available to them and, if necessary, create new ones to provide the financial markets and the economy with enough liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net lending in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to be able to provide further budget support.
Under extraordinary circumstances and in countries without access to capital markets, official lending could be complemented by debt restructuring.
The MDBs should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role in this.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unprecedented in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis should not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-won civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer to citizens.
